==[[Pronunciation]]==
*British English [[w:IPA|IPA]]: /'skwɒʃ/
*American English [[w:IPA|IPA]]: /'skwɑʃ/

==[[Noun]]==

1.A game much like rackets, played in a walled court with soft
rubber balls and bats like tennis rackets.

2. [Cf. {Musquash}.] (Zo["o]l.) An American animal allied to the weasel. ([[Obs.]]) --Goldsmith.

3. (Bot.)A plant and its fruit of the genus [[w:Cucurbita|Cucurbita]], or gourd kind.

Note: The species are much confused. The long-neck squash is called Cucurbita verrucosa, the Barbary or China squash, C. moschata, and the great winter squash, C. maxima, but the distinctions are not clear.

4. Something soft and easily crushed; especially, an unripe pod of pease.

         Not yet old enough for a man, nor young enough for a boy; as a squash is before 't is a peascod. --Shak.

5. Hence, something unripe or soft; -- used in contempt.
   ``This squash, this gentleman.'' --Shak.

6. A sudden fall of a heavy, soft body; also, a shock of soft bodies. --Arbuthnot.

         My fall was stopped by a terrible squash. --Swift
 
{Squash beetle} ([[Zool.]]), a small American beetle ({Diabrotica, or Galeruca vittata}) which is often abundant and very injurious to the leaves of squash,   cucumber, etc. It is striped with yellow and black. The name is applied also to other allied species.

{Squash [[bug]]} (Zool.), a large black American hemipterous insect ({Coreus, or Anasa, tristis}) injurious to squash vines.

